Paintings and sculpture from the Kress Collection. Acquired by the Samuel H. Kress Foundation 1945-1951, Washington 1951 (Catalogue by W. Suida), p. 204. [nr.] 90 Pieter Bruegel the Elder, Landscape with the Temptation of St. Anthony (repr. p. 205) Since its rediscovery this painting has been recognized as a work by P. Bruegel and published by L. van Puyvelde (Pantheon XV, 1935), M.J. Friedländer (N.Mal. XIV, 1937), G. Glück (1936 &Jb. 1935). These critics agree that it is one of the earlier paintings by P.B. of about 1557-1558, and that it shows close connection with the landscape in the coll. Stuyck del Bruyère dated 1557 (now on exhibition as a loan in the N.G. of Art Washington; [verso] Charles de Tolnay (1935), on the other hand, considers it an early work by Jan Bruegel. Wood, Oak: 2211/15 x 33 9/16in. (57,8 x 85,3 cm). Formerly in the coll. of the Countess Montblanc, Belgium. L. van Puyvelde (Pantheon XV, 1935) says the painting was overpainted and neglected until one day et fell down from the wall, so that repairs became inevitable. When cleaned it was recognized as a P.B. S.H. Kress Coll. New York 1950. Exh. Brussels 1935, Paris Orangerie 1936(7) Baltimore Mus. of Art 1943 & 1948; Raleigh, the Carolina State Society Art Gallery, 1943.",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] Ad [Addendum] 42. WASHINGTON, Nat. Gallery of Art. Paintings and sculpture from the Kress Collection. Acquired by the Samuel H. Kress Foundation 1945-1951, Washington 1951 (Catalogue by W. Suida), p. 204. [nr.] 90 Pieter Bruegel the Elder, Landscape with the Temptation of St. Anthony (repr. p. 205) Since its rediscovery this painting has been recognized as a work by P. Bruegel and published by L. van Puyvelde (Pantheon XV, 1935), M.J. Friedländer (N.Mal. XIV, 1937), G. Glück (1936 &Jb. 1935). These critics agree that it is one of the earlier paintings by P.B. of about 1557-1558, and that it shows close connection with the landscape in the coll. Stuyck del Bruyère dated 1557 (now on exhibition as a loan in the N.G. of Art Washington; [verso] Charles de Tolnay (1935), on the other hand, considers it an early work by Jan Bruegel. Wood, Oak: 2211/15 x 33 9/16in. (57,8 x 85,3 cm). Formerly in the coll. of the Countess Montblanc, Belgium. L. van Puyvelde (Pantheon XV, 1935) says the painting was overpainted and neglected until one day et fell down from the wall, so that repairs became inevitable. When cleaned it was recognized as a P.B. S.H. Kress Coll. New York 1950. Exh. Brussels 1935, Paris Orangerie 1936(7) Baltimore Mus. of Art 1943 & 1948; Raleigh, the Carolina State Society Art Gallery, 1943.</content>
